{"id":"project-LICHEN-k1dt","title":"codec.rs: BitReader::read returns wrong error type for partial byte reads","description":"File: rust/lichen-schc/src/codec.rs
Lines: 126-140 (BitReader::read)

Category: CORRECTNESS

The BitReader::read() function computes required bits and compares against available bits:
```rust
fn read(&mut self, nbits: usize) -> Result<u128, SchcError> {
    let required_bits = self.pos + nbits;
    let available_bits = self.buf.len() * 8;
    if required_bits > available_bits {
        return Err(TooShort::new(required_bits.div_ceil(8), self.buf.len()).into());
    }
    ...
}
```

The error reports byte counts (required_bits.div_ceil(8) vs self.buf.len()), but the actual shortage may be less than a full byte. For example:
- Buffer has 2 bytes (16 bits), already read 15 bits (pos=15)
- Trying to read 4 bits (required_bits=19)
- Error: TooShort(3, 2) - "need 3 bytes, have 2"
- But actually we only need 19 bits (2.375 bytes)

This is technically accurate since we do need at least 3 bytes to have 19 bits, but the error message may be misleading when debugging partial-byte edge cases.

Impact: Minor - error messages are slightly imprecise but functionally correct.

